            <notesStmt>
                <note type="summary">
                    
                        
                            
                            <p>A letter from  James H. Hampton (1858-1931) to Robert Chalmers (1858-1938), the under-secretary for Ireland. In the letter Hampton complains about receiving a Roman Catholic pastoral letter which was forwarded by the Chief Secretary's Office, despite the fact he is a member of the Church of Ireland. He goes on to state that considering the position of the Bishop of Limerick, Edward Thomas O'Dwyer (1842-1917) who openly supported the Rising, the government should not be forwarding such letters, or at least keep them within the Catholic community. He goes on to state that the issue will be brought to the House of Commons if it occurs again.</p>
                            
                        
                            
                        
                            
                            <p>Sir Robert Chalmers was sent to Ireland as replacement under-secretary for Sir Matthew Nathan, who had resigned along with Augustine Birrell, his chief secretary, following the outbreak of the Easter Rising in 1916.</p>
                            
                        
                    
                </note>
