<opener><address><addrLine>2 Merille</addrLine>
<addrLine>Queenstown,</addrLine></address>
<dateline><date>2<hi rend="superscript">nd</hi> June 1916.</date></dateline>

<salute>Sir,</salute></opener>

<p>I received today from the Chief Secretary's Office 
<lb/>a Pastoral letter on Thrift by the Roman Catholic 
<lb/>Bishop of Meath. I have not read the Pastoral 
<lb/>nor do I intend to do so. I consider that an 
<lb/>unwarranted insult has been offered to me, as a 
<lb/>clergyman of the Church of Ireland, in sending 
<lb/>me a Pastoral by a Roman Catholic Bishop, 
<lb/>I am especially since it was forwarded "On His Majesty's Service".
<lb/>When I consider the attitude taken up by the Roman 
<lb/>Catholic Bishop of Limerick with reference to the 
<lb/>Sinn Fein <unclear>inflammation</unclear> and the recent rebellion, one 
<lb/>would imagine that His Majesty's Government would 
<lb/>have something better to do than to send Roman Catholic 
<lb/>Pastorals <gap/> throughout the country, and that 
<lb/>they would at least confine them to the members of 
<lb/>their own Communion. If any such literature is forwarded 
<lb/>to me again, I shall take steps to have the matter raised 
<lb/>in the House of Commons.</p>

<closer><salute>Yours faithfully,</salute>
<signed><hi rend="underline">James H. Hampton</hi></signed>

<address><addrLine>The Under Secretary for Ireland</addrLine>
<addrLine><hi rend="underline">Dublin Castle</hi></addrLine></address></closer>
        
    

    
                </body>
            </text>

        
            
        

         

